<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910702-0102</DOCNO><DOCID>910702-0102.</DOCID><HL>   Kuwait Said to Reach   Terms With Citibank   On Major Borrowing   ----   Special to The Wall Street Journal</HL><DATE>07/02/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A9</SO><CO>   CCI</CO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>MAJOR MONEY CENTER BANKS (BAN)ALL BANKS, BANKING NEWS AND ISSUES (BNK)BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)SECURITIES (SCR)</IN><NS>BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)</NS><RE>ARABIAN PENINSULA (ARA)EUROPE (EU)KUWAIT (KU)MIDDLE EAST (ML)NORTH AMERICA (NME)NEW YORK (NY)GREAT BRITAIN (UK)UNITED STATES (US)WESTERN EUROPE (WEU)</RE><LP>   LONDON -- The Kuwait government has reached terms on itsfirst postwar borrowing, a $500 million securities repurchaseagreement with a major U.S. bank, according to Westernfinancial officials.   The Kuwait Investment Authority, which manages Kuwait'sestimated $60 billion overseas investment portfolio, and ishandling negotiations with prospective lenders over postwarloans to the Persian Gulf state, agreed to terms last monthwith Citicorp's Citibank on the three-month credit, theseofficials said.</LP><TEXT>   Citibank's general-purpose loan to the Kuwait governmentis backed by bonds and other securities already held by theU.S. bank in investment portfolios it manages on behalf ofthe Kuwait Investment Authority and its London-based arm, theKuwait Investment Office, they added.   Details of the exact securities pledged against thecredit, the quality of the securities pledged and the pricingof the repurchase agreement couldn't be determinedimmediately.   What is known, is that the facility, which apparentlyhasn't yet been drawn upon, can be rolled over at maturity.   Citibank, like other banks currently in talks with Kuwaitiofficials, declined to comment. The bank is believed, though,to have included terms that call for further KuwaitInvestment Authority-controlled securities to be put up ascollateral if the value of the securities already pledgeddepreciate before the repurchase matures.</TEXT></DOC>